Mixing SCPs is virtually always  - in fact most of the senior staff take great delight in telling you that the worst case scenario you THOUGHT you had come up with might be the BEST that you could get. For example:

We don't understand 138 already. For all we know, he's UNdead. The process could destroy him. This, by the way, is probably the BEST that would happen.
Prolonged exposure to 427 results in a  - assuming you use a normal person. 138 seems to be unkillable already. This is a BAD combination.
138 was locked away. Some make the mistake of thinking he should be healed. He was stabbed seventeen times. And had his throat cut. Then put in a stone box and hidden from what someone probably thought was all eternity. I'm not too eager to have this guy up and about.


Read the destruction logs of attempts to kill 682. The ones that turn out the WORST are the one where they try to use another SCP to destroy it.

Somewhere there's a story of where they mix five  SCPs. I don't remember the name of the story, but it's a very Bright day







